{"key":"processedPost-10261189","value":{"id":10261189,"first":10257513,"last":14923768,"when":1241101698,"utime":"04/30/09 05:28 PM","content":"Jesus, trichoderma will NOT grow on plain gypsum.&nbsp; It will however grow on peat moss and we use that in casing layers.&nbsp; The idea of a non-nutritive casing layer is to make it somewhat inhospitable to molds.&nbsp; If your casing layer was completely inert, such as perlite, it would never colonize.&nbsp; Use gypsum in casing layers and substrates.&nbsp; This has been established in mycology and by professional mushroom farms for decades.&nbsp; It's not something new.<br />RR","title":"Re: Adding gypsum to what is supposed to be a non-nutritive casing layer"}}